{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648918"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:59:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:59:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18334"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18334"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11052"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74286"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11052"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18334"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59777"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"},{"type":"tags","id":"11271"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25643"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74286"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology of calcific tendinitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autoimmune attack on joint tissues","Deposition of calcium hydroxyapatite crystals in tendons","Degeneration of cartilage in weight-bearing joints","Formation of urate crystals in joint spaces","Inflammation of the synovial membrane"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECalcific tendinitis is a condition that affects tendons, particularly in the shoulder region. It is characterised by the deposition of calcium crystals within the tendon tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pathophysiology of calcific tendinitis involves the \u003Cstrong\u003Edeposition of calcium hydroxyapatite crystals in tendons\u003C/strong\u003E. This is most commonly seen in the rotator cuff tendons of the shoulder. The presence of these calcium deposits can lead to inflammation and pain as the body mounts an inflammatory response to the foreign material.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of urate crystals in joint spaces\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes gout, not calcific tendinitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDegeneration of cartilage in weight-bearing joints\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of osteoarthritis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammation of the synovial membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - This is typical of synovitis, not calcific tendinitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune attack on joint tissues\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes rheumatoid arthritis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcific tendinitis is distinct in its specific involvement of calcium crystal deposition within tendons, leading to the clinical symptoms associated with the condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcific tendinitis is characterised by the deposition of calcium hydroxyapatite crystals in tendons, most commonly affecting the rotator cuff.","The condition is thought to result from a combination of degenerative changes and local tissue hypoxia.","Calcific tendinitis can lead to inflammation and pain due to the body\u0027s inflammatory response to the calcium deposits."],"references":["Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Datta HK, Ng WF, Walker JA, Tuck SP, Varanasi SS. The cell biology of bone metabolism. J Clin Pathol. 2008 May;61(5):577-87. doi: 10.1136/jcp.2007.048868. PMID: 18441154","Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59777"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18334"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59777"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T04:13:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T04:14:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11052"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74286"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","n